               <p>JOHN BEALE. I live in <placeName id="t18270215-2-crimeloc6">Union-street, Hoxton</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270215-2-crimeloc6" type="placeName" value="Union-street, Hoxton"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270215-2-crimeloc6" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270215-2-off4 t18270215-2-crimeloc6"></join>, and am a <rs id="t18270215-2-viclabel7" type="occupation">baker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270215-2-victim93 t18270215-2-viclabel7"></join>. On the 3d of February, about six o'clock in the evening, I was sitting in the parlour; no one was in the shop, and the door was shut - I heard a rustling in the shop, and saw the prisoner going out; I ran, and secured him outside the door - he then threw down my till, which had 13s. in copper in it; he must have come into the shop on his hands and knees - he lives in the neighbourhood, and is apprenticed to a brass screw maker: an officer came and took him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270215-2-person94">
                  RICHARD 
                  CONSTANTINE
               <interp inst="t18270215-2-person94" type="surname" value="CONSTANTINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270215-2-person94" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270215-2-person94" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a headborough. I took charge of the prisoner, and found four bottles of blacking on him; I asked how he came to do this - he said he had no other means of getting his living. The till was then on the counter, and contained 13s. in copper.</p>
               <p>
